The novelist{Elizabeth Gaskell,} who was a friend of the famous{Bronte {Sisters,}spent the later years of her life at{'The Lawn',}an old house in Holybourne, and died there in 1865 aged 55, but her body, together with that of her husband is buried in the graveyard in Knutsford, the town she immortalised as{'Cranford'}in her novel of that name. She also wrote { {'The Life of Charlotte Bronte'.}
There is now a road in Holybourne called{'Gaskell Close',}and another called{'Cranford Drive'}in memory of Mrs Gaskell and her writings.
'The Lawn' still stands, and is now an old people's home.
